{{EncelGeo-Crater
|name=Behram
|picture=[[Image:EN Zumurrud crater.jpg|250px|]]<br><small>Behram (top center) as seen<br>by the ''Cassini'' spacecraft on July 14, 2005</small>
|location={{Coord|15.41|S|181.02|W|globe:enceladus|notes=<ref name=gpn>{{Gpn|14238|Behram}}</ref>}}
|diameter=13.7&nbsp;km<ref name=gpn />
|depth=
|discoverer=''[[Cassini–Huygens|Cassini]]''
|naming=Behram; The fictional son of a Persian King from "Prince Behram and the Princess Al-Datma."
}}

'''Behram''' is an [[impact crater]] on the anti-Saturn hemisphere of [[Saturn]]'s moon [[Enceladus (moon)|Enceladus]].  Behram was first observed in ''[[Cassini-Huygens Mission|Cassini]]'' images during that mission's March 2005 flyby of Enceladus.  It is located at 15.4° South [[Latitude]], 181.0° West [[Longitude]], and is 13.7 kilometers across.<ref name=gpn />  Behram's rim overlaps that of [[Shakashik (crater)|Shakashik]], suggesting that Behram formed after Shakashik.  Following formation, numerous criss-crossing fractures cut across Behram, forming canyons hundreds of meters deep along the crater's rim, as well as a region of disrupted terrain on the crater floor.  The International Astronomical Union (IAU) adopted the S. Behram designation for feature ID 14238 in 2007.

