{{Infobox rockunit | name = Cumbrian Coast Group | image = | caption = | type = [[Group (stratigraphy)|Group]] | age = [[Permian]] | prilithology = [[siltstone]] | otherlithology = [[mudstone]], [[anhydrite]], [[sandstone]] | namedfor = coast of [[Cumbria]] | namedby = | region = | country = [[England]] | coordinates = | unitof = | subunits = St Bees Shale Formation, St Bees Evaporite Formation, Barrowmouth Mudstone Formation, Eden Shales Formation | underlies = [[Sherwood Sandstone Group]] | overlies = [[Appleby Group]] | thickness = | extent = | area = | map = | map_caption = }}
The '''Cumbrian Coast Group''' is a [[Permian]] [[lithostratigraphy|lithostratigraphic]] [[group (stratigraphy)|group]] (a sequence of [[rock strata]]) which occurs in the western part of [[Cumbria]] in northern [[England]].
==Distribution and stratigraphy== The group outcrops near [[Whitehaven]] on the Cumbrian coast and beneath the [[Vale of Eden]]. It comprises the St Bees Evaporite and the overlying St Bees Shale Formation which are between 0 and 100m and 0 and 215m thick respectively.<ref>British Geological Survey 1:50,000 scale map sheet (England and Wales series) no 28 ''Whitehaven'')</ref> The lower formation sits atop the mixed lithology [[breccia]] known as [[Brockram]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bgs.ac.uk/Lexicon/lexicon.cfm?pub=CCO|title=BGS Lexicon of Named Rock Units - Result Details|website=Bgs.ac.uk|accessdate=14 November 2018}}</ref> It is also found beneath the [[Irish Sea]] where the Barrowmouth Mudstone Formation is the equivalent of the St Bees Shale Formation.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bgs.ac.uk/Lexicon/lexicon.cfm?pub=BAMU|title=BGS Lexicon of Named Rock Units|website=Bgs.ac.uk|accessdate=14 November 2018}}</ref> The Group can achieve thicknesses in excess of 300m here.
