{{DEFAULTSORT:Q.E.D. (Bbc Tv Series)}} [[Category:1982 British television programme debuts]] [[Category:1999 British television programme endings]] [[Category:BBC television documentaries about science]] [[Category:Documentary television series about technology]] [[Category:Popular science]] [[Category:Science education in the United Kingdom]] [[Category:1980s British documentary television series]] [[Category:1990s British documentary television series]]

In [[biology]], especially [[marine biology]], '''recruitment''' occurs when a juvenile organism joins a [[population]], whether by birth or immigration, usually at a stage whereby the organisms are settled and able to be detected by an observer.<ref>[http://www.biology-online.org/dictionary/Recruitment Recruitment]. Biology Online. Accessed October 21, 2012.</ref><ref>[http://hixon.science.oregonstate.edu/files/hixon/publications/038%20-%20Caley%20et%20al%2096%20ARES.pdf Recruitment and the Local Dynamics of Open Marine Populations]. Annual Review of Ecology and Systematics 1996. 27:477–500</ref> 

There are two types of recruitment: closed and open.{{what|date=February 2015}}

In the study of [[fishery|fisheries]], recruitment is "the number of fish surviving to enter the fishery or to some life history stage such as settlement or maturity".<ref>[http://www.gov.scot/Topics/marine/marine-environment/ecosystems/population/recruitment Fish recruitment]. The Scottish Government. Accessed January 14, 2016.</ref>

